Hi,

Why do you think JSON-LD doesn&#39;t utilize link relations? They are just more
terse. Let&#39;s look at an example:

{
  &quot;@context&quot;: {
    &quot;homepage&quot;: { &quot;@id&quot;: http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/homepage&quot;, &quot;@type&quot;: &quot;@id&quot;
}
    }
  },
  &quot;name&quot;: &quot;Markus Lanthaler&quot;,
  &quot;homepage&quot;: &quot;http://www.markus-lanthaler.com/&quot;
}


This (incomplete) JSON-LD document would tell you that there&#39;s a JSON object
which has a key &quot;homepage&quot; that represents a homepage according to the FOAF
vocabulary - that&#39;s the rel part, isn&#39;t it!? The value of it is
&quot;http://www.markus-lanthaler.com/&quot;. The coercion in the context tells a
JSON-LD parser that it is an IRI and not just a string and thus allows a
client to follow that link.

See also Manu Sporny&#39;s comment on Mark Notthingsham&#39;s blog post about
&quot;Linking in JSON&quot; [1]. I think there is still some confusion about what
JSON-LD is (intended to be).


[1] http://www.mnot.net/blog/2011/11/25/linking_in_json#comment-1737



