&gt; Hi Markus,
&gt; 
&gt; at a first glance your referred papers are looking very promising. They
&gt; remind me to a discussion we had appr. one year ago about the
&gt; REST-i-ness of SPARQL (see [1]).
&gt; However, the problem with JSON-LD still is, that it doesn&#39;t utilise
&gt; link
&gt; relation types (as it is the same problem with all RDF serialisation
&gt; formats ATM). In contrast, HAL makes use of link relations types
&gt; (&quot;href&quot;, ...), and, hence, supports the HATEOAS constraint of REST.
&gt; So my solution proposal for this problem still is to design a
&gt; vocabulary
&gt; to describe link relation type definitions in a machine processable way
&gt; and attach these definitions to our well-known RDF property
&gt; definitions,
&gt; i.e., then we have knowledge about the property (relation) itself and
&gt; how it can be processed by a client.
